      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're correct in a sense that high tariffs could potentially motivate companies to relocate manufacturing back to their home country to avoid paying the tariffs. However, this 'reshoring' of manufacturing isn't guaranteed. Companies weigh various factors, including labor costs, production capabilities, access to raw materials, and proximity to markets. If tariffs make imported goods significantly more expensive than locally produced goods, they could prompt some reshoring. Still, if tariffs are too high, they could lead to consumers facing higher prices without necessarily achieving the desired domestic job growth. Moreover, this could also lead to retaliatory tariffs from other countries, affecting exports and potentially harming the very job creation you aim to protect.",
